         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"unitaryCircle\" id=\"circtri0\"><style>.circle-draw circle, .circle-draw line {stroke: #71a6d2; stroke-width: 4; stroke-linecap: round; fill: none;} .circle-draw circle { stroke-dasharray: 942; stroke-dashoffset: 942; animation: drawCircle 2s linear forwards;} .radius-line { transform-origin: 300px 170px; animation: rotateRadius 2s linear forwards;} .radius-45 { opacity: 0; animation: showRadius45 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2s; } .radius-30{ opacity: 0; animation: showRadius30 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2s; } .vertical45 { opacity: 0; animation: showVertical45 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2.5s; } .atlasTextRadius { opacity: 0; animation: atlasTextRadiusMov 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2.8s; }</style><style>@keyframes drawCircle { to {stroke-dashoffset: 0; } } @keyframes rotateRadius { from { transform: rotate(0deg); } to   { transform: rotate(-360deg); } } @keyframes showRadius45 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } } @keyframes showRadius30 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }  @keyframes showVertical45 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }  @keyframes atlasTextRadiusMov { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }</style><div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 340\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"3\" markerHeight=\"3\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <path class=\"radius-30\" d=\"M 320 147 A 30 30 0 0 1 340.0 170.0\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#71a6d2\" stroke-width=\"3\"/> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"470\" y2=\"169\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"8\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"130\" y2=\"169\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"330\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"170\" r=\"148\" transform=\"scale(-1 1) translate(-600 0)  rotate(180 300 170)\"></circle> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"448\" y2=\"169\"></line> <line class=\"radius-45\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"406\" y2=\"66\"></line>  <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"406\" y1=\"66\" x2=\"406\" y2=\"166\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"360\" y=\"188\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">c</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"360\" y=\"88\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">c</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"360\" y=\"158\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">a</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"390\" y=\"128\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">b</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"320\" y=\"165\" font-size=\"1.0em\" font-weight=\"bold\">θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"407\" y=\"65\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text>  <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"405\" y=\"182\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">Q</text></svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 1</b>: Circle with a radius of 1 containing a right triangle.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Trigonometry (Cosine)\n\nIn the previous text, we explored how to draw a right triangle and saw that, through the legs of the triangle or the hypotenuse, from the center we could reach any point **P** located on the circle.\n\nIn addition to the paths via the triangle, we also learned that, as a ray moves away from the horizontal line, we create an angle theta (θ) that we have not yet explored. This fact leads us to a reflection.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: How can I help you?</b><br /><br />Knowing that the angle theta (θ) represents the opening of the ray, which in turn is related to the hypotenuse of the right triangle.<br /><br />How can we connect this angle to the legs?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Trigonometry\n\nBefore establishing the relationship between the angle, the legs, and the hypotenuse, it is necessary to observe exactly what happens when the ray (the hypotenuse of the right triangle) rotates to create the circle, so that we can obtain relationships that accurately reproduce what we are observing.\n\nLet's make a list of everything we need to reproduce in the relationships:\n1. The horizontal leg **a** has its greatest length when the rotating ray is in the horizontal position. Meanwhile, the vertical leg **b** has its greatest length when the ray is in the vertical positions.\n2. The angle theta (θ) increases from the horizontal, counterclockwise (from right to left).\n3. Regarding the smallest length of the horizontal and vertical legs, this occurs precisely when the other leg is at its maximum value. That is: the horizontal leg **a** has its smallest size when the vertical leg **b** has its greatest value, and vice versa.\n4. For all the described scenarios, the ray (the hypotenuse) always has a single length. The horizontal and vertical legs reach their maximum values when they equal the length of the ray.\n\nThe detailed study of these relationships is known as trigonometry (<htcite0>). This study is done through trigonometric functions, which we introduce next.\n\n#### Cosine\n\nThe first trigonometric function we introduce is the cosine, defined in **Formula 1** (<htcite1>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0098b5fe-1cb7-4451-82c9-8e5d5d4f20e6",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Trigonometry",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "92e66bd4-1d7f-4f28-bed2-f62210493341",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Cossine",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><math display=\"block\"><mn>cos (θ)</mn><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>adjacent leg</mi><mi>hypotenuse</mi></mfrac></math></p></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 1</b>: Definition of cosine.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: The definition of cosine</b><br /><br />Does the definition of cosine presented in <b>Formula 1</b> manage to represent everything we described regarding leg <b>a</b>, the angle, and the hypotenuse?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The maximum value\n\nTo answer this reflection, we need to analyze all the points listed when talking about trigonometry. To simplify our understanding, we will do this by isolating parts of **Graph 1** that correspond to the study we are developing.\n\nWhen the ray **c** is exactly on the horizontal line, this causes leg **a** to have the same length as it (**Graph 2**):",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 170\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"3\" markerHeight=\"3\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <path d=\"M 348 150 A 148 148 0 0 0 200 2\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#71a6d2\" stroke-width=\"3\"/> <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"150\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"150\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"200\" y1=\"149\" x2=\"348\" y2=\"149\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"260\" y=\"147\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">c</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"180\" y=\"149\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"350\" y=\"149\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text>  <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"260\" y=\"165\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">a</text> </svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 2</b>: The hypotenuse over the adjacent leg without the angle theta (θ).</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Since leg **a** has the same length as ray **c** in **Graph 2**, that is, **a = c**, the cosine of theta (θ) —for when there is no angle separating two rays— will be the greatest possible value: 1, as shown in **Calculation 1** (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><math display=\"block\"><mn>cos (θ)</mn><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>adjacent leg</mi><mi>hypotenuse</mi></mfrac><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Maximum value obtained for the cosine of theta (θ).</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Intermediate Values\n\nWhen the radius begins to rotate, the angle theta (θ) starts to assume a value different from zero, as shown in **Graph 3**.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 160\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"3\" markerHeight=\"3\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <path d=\"M 348 150 A 148 148 0 0 0 200 2\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#71a6d2\" stroke-width=\"3\"/> <path class=\"radius-30\" d=\"M 230 130 A 30 30 0 0 1 240.0 150.0\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#71a6d2\" stroke-width=\"3\"/> <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"150\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"150\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"200\" y1=\"149\" x2=\"320\" y2=\"149\"></line> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"319\" y1=\"149\" x2=\"320\" y2=\"67\"></line> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"200\" y1=\"149\" x2=\"319\" y2=\"67\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"250\" y=\"89\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">c</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"180\" y=\"150\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"325\" y=\"65\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text>  <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"260\" y=\"146\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">a</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"223\" y=\"146\" font-size=\"1.0em\" font-weight=\"bold\">θ</text> </svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 3</b>: Angle theta (θ) between the hypotenuse and the adjacent leg.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Another observed consequence of this rotation of the radius is the decrease in the size of leg **a**. This does not happen by chance: it occurs because leg a represents the projection of the hypotenuse **c** onto the base.\n\nThese two behaviors we have described have direct consequences for the cosine of theta (θ). As leg a (the projection) decreases in size, the value of the cosine also decreases, because we are dividing smaller values of a leg by a constant, the hypotenuse.\n\n#### The Smallest Value\n\nThe smallest possible value we are visualizing in the graphs on this page will occur when leg **a** has a length equal to zero. This will happen whenever the radius (our hypotenuse) is completely vertical, as shown in **Graph 4**.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 160\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"3\" markerHeight=\"3\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <path d=\"M 348 150 A 148 148 0 0 0 200 2\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#71a6d2\" stroke-width=\"3\"/> <path class=\"radius-30\" d=\"M 200 120 A 30 30 0 0 1 230.0 150.0\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#71a6d2\" stroke-width=\"3\"/> <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"150\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"150\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"200\" y1=\"149\" x2=\"200\" y2=\"4\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"180\" y=\"89\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">c</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"180\" y=\"150\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"180\" y=\"15\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"208\" y=\"146\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">θ</text> </svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 4</b>: Completely inclined radius.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Something more needs to be said about **Graph 4**. Despite the projection of the radius onto the horizontal being zero when the radius is vertical, the angle theta (θ) is still present.\n\n#### Conclusions\n\nThe cosine of theta (θ) perfectly represents the projection of leg a as the radius rotates around center **O**. This information is even demonstrated in **Formula 1** and can be made explicit by multiplying both sides of it by the hypotenuse (the radius **c**):",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><math display=\"block\"><mn>cos (θ)</mn><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac></math></p> <p><math display=\"block\"><mn>(c) cos (θ)</mn><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac><mn>(c)</mn></math></p> <p><math display=\"block\"><mn>(c) cos (θ)</mn><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mn>a (1)</mn></math></p> <p><math display=\"block\"><mn>(c) cos (θ)</mn><mo lspace=\"0.1667em\" rspace=\"0.1667em\">=</mo><mn>a</mn></math></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Projection of the hypotenuse onto the horizontal axis.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "From **Calculation 2**, we can confirm the data present in the list provided in the *Trigonometry* section above:\n- **Line 1**: This line tells us that as leg **a** grows from the center **O**, it will reach its greatest size when it attains the maximum possible length within the circle: the length of the radius **c**. Consequently, the cosine, in this case, will be equal to 1. On the other hand, as the leg decreases from the edge of the circle, the cosine of theta will reduce until it reaches zero, which corresponds to the center. This description matches items *1, 3 and 4* of the *Trigonometry* section.\n- **Line 2**: The radius **c** functions as a limiter on both sides of the calculation. To understand how the leg is influenced by it and by the angle, it is necessary to add both sides repeatedly until the size of the radius **c**, is reached; that is, we multiply both sides by **c**.\n- **Line 3**: Since on the right side we were already dividing by the size of the radius, this means that on that side, we obtained the total value, which allows us to replace it with 1.\n- **Line 4**: Finally, this line informs us that as the value of the cosine decreases, leg **a** reduces its length. This event occurs precisely because the angle is increasing, and as a consequence, the projection **a** is decreasing. This last line corresponds exactly to *item 2* of the list in the *Trigonometry* section.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
